rComments: He clearly loves what he teaches. His lecture is filled with videos that clear up concepts. There is a lot of reading and is based off the textbook but the readings are simple and enjoyable. Definitely a course to take with Prof Chen. 1 midterm and final and easy weekly assignments.

The professor replies quickly to emails and is able to accommodate reasonable student requests. The course material is interesting and the testing was straightforward multiple choice all from the textbook.

Professor Chen's lectures are useless. He is impossible to understand 9 times out of 10, and writes extremely small on the board. He assigns a ridiculous amount of homework which you cannot complete with only lecture material; the textbook will be your best friend. The midterm was VERY hard and the exam did not reflect lecture material. Good luck.

Chen makes the course near impossible without his insane levels of grade curving. You come out feeling like you know near nothing about the subject. No solutions to the assignments are given, so you don't have feedback in that way. No past finals are given as practice for the upcoming exams and the exam itself was unreasonably difficult.

No, just no. Assignments were EXTREMELY time consuming, and relatively difficult. On top of that, the midterm&final were completely unreasonable. Midterm avg was approx 30%, and he only told us that he'd only curve after the final. Thus, most of us went in the final with a terrible grade.... Final was even worse, so who knows what our fate is.

The only course I failed in my 4 years of studying physics. I got an E. I did not even know this grade exists. Half the class dropped out before November and 5 people failed (out of 12, I think). Those who dropped out, hoped to take the course with Pawel Hawrylak, but Chen is teaching again. We are all going for exchange to other universities.

One of the only physics profs able to present the class material in an engaging way (regardless of how off-the-wall complex is it). He's extremely nice and funny. Assignments range from fair to very difficult, exams are ruthless and don't reflect the assignments. However, he is an EXTREMELY lenient marker with many bonus points available.

I like professor Chen a lot, he clearly likes teaching, and really knows his stuff. The homework hard, but he gave everyone in the class a pdf copy of the textbook which was very helpful. He goes pretty fast in lectures, I found it was easiest just to listen to him and read the textbook later, rather than trying to take good notes.

Prof Chang is very knowledgeable, just tough to communicate with. His assignments are very easy, the midterm was exactly what was seen in class. If you don't go to class and rely only on the book, you'll have too wide a margin of content to study for. Go to every lecture (full of Youtube videos, yay?), you'll pass everything easily. Recommended.
teacherRatingTags: ['Clear grading criteria', 'Accessible outside class', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Assignments are very difficult. Exams are impossible (a midterm average of 30% is not unusual). The grading, however, is very lenient (e.g. exam with 65 maximum points got marked out of 35). All of this turns out to be a great thing because it really motivates you to learn, and you WILL learn a lot.

Prof. Chen is one of my fave profs! He is extremely dedicated, knowledgeable, helpful and clear in his explanations. He does many examples. Obviously the class is difficult and requires work but he is one of the few teachers who actually really want you to succeed and enjoy this topic. I would take another class with him!
Awesome prof. Difficult assignments, midterm and exam, but you really learn a lot in his class and he marks very kindly.

Extremely difficult professor, his expectations of his students are ridiculous. That being said, you do learn a lot in his class. If you get 60% on his test, chances are it will get curved to 100%, since the class average before the curve is usually in the 40's.

Very good prof, keep you interested the whole semester. Difficult assignments but they're good previews of the exams. Very fairly graded by the prof (TA does assignments). Could use a few more examples in class. Very useful textbook (Mathematics for Physicist by Lea)
Good professor if you work hard. Also hot.

Very good professor. Explains all the concepts with extrem clarity and solves plenty of examples in class. Very helpful when you go see him in his office. However,you must work very hard for his exams.

Terrible Prof. Doesn't prepare notes ahead of time but makes them up as he goes along. Barely speaks English. No examples done in class. Assignments are reasonable, but the exams are completely different from anything covered on the assignments and have no apparent relation to anything covered in class. I got an A+, but I have no idea how.

Worst prof ever. Exams filled with trick questions and penalties for wrong answers. Barely solves any examples in class and when he does, you cant understand them. This year, he picked the worst possible T.A. to give students and additional challange in his course

WorSt ever. i understand nothing in his classes..he explains nothing..all his examples in the notes are left blank with no clue to solve..exams are difficult..JUST DONT THINK ABOUT TAKING ANY COURSE WITH HIM...A GUY WHO SOLVES PHYSICS IN POWER POINT SLIDES ONLY AND U CANT UNDERSTAND ANY WORD COMING FROM HIS MOUTH.

He is one of the worst teachers in that school.He might have good intentions but thats not what counts.If you are reading this sir,please STOP making discouraging comments to your students-" if you dont know this then i cant help you".Thats why you're there sir.In sum,unhelpful notes,unclear lecture,unfair penalty on multiply choice.
